{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-blog-post-js","path":"/blog/how-good-accessibility-improves-user-experiences-business-profit/","result":{"data":{"site":{"siteMetadata":{"title":"Ordina Bold Tech & Design Blog","configs":{"countOfInitialPost":10}}},"markdownRemark":{"id":"d883dd50-1b04-56fe-bd16-194744e1307d","excerpt":"Introduction When was the last time you used a website or application and got frustrated because you had trouble using it? Maybe the digital application used some technology your browser didn’t support, or you couldn’t read its text because the font size was too small or maybe…","html":"<h2 id=\"introduction\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#introduction\" aria-label=\"introduction permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Introduction</h2>\n<p>When was the last time you used a website or application and got frustrated because you had trouble using it? Maybe the digital application used some technology your browser didn’t support, or you couldn’t read its text because the font size was too small or maybe you couldn’t see the images correctly because of the sunlight. When you look back on this situation you have experienced inaccessibility.</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>“Accessibility is treating everyone, no matter what their ability, the same.”</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>This quote makes a lot of sense when you think of it. We are all different. This means we want everyone to have the ability to access &#x26; benefit from some system or entity. Either physical or digital. The end goal is to enable access for people with disabilities using assistive technology. Having it top of mind while designing will improve the UX of your site for not only disabled individuals but for the public as well. It will also save potential headaches in the future from lawsuits and angry customers.</p>\n<p>An amazing example of good accessibility in the real world is tactile pavements. It is an organism of raised surface markers so that people with bad vision or blindness can easily detect them with a cane or foot. These blocks are so simple but solves so much.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 780px; \"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 56.41025641025641%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"image 1\"\n        title=\"image 1\"\n        src=\"/static/c0e6f003a056aa96299fafe2d650f705/be796/image-1.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/c0e6f003a056aa96299fafe2d650f705/4146e/image-1.jpg 195w,\n/static/c0e6f003a056aa96299fafe2d650f705/e52b6/image-1.jpg 390w,\n/static/c0e6f003a056aa96299fafe2d650f705/be796/image-1.jpg 780w,\n/static/c0e6f003a056aa96299fafe2d650f705/ad68d/image-1.jpg 1170w,\n/static/c0e6f003a056aa96299fafe2d650f705/62522/image-1.jpg 1560w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 780px) 100vw, 780px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<h2 id=\"digital-accessibility\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#digital-accessibility\" aria-label=\"digital accessibility permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Digital accessibility</h2>\n<p>Digital products are designed &#x26; developed so that people with disabilities can use them. According to last US census results, about 19% of the United States population identifies as having a disability.  A lot of us think that having a disability is based on something you’ll have for all your life but that’s not true. We can distinguish 6 types of disabilities:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Aging population</li>\n<li>Users who don’t speak the same language</li>\n<li>Users with cognitive limitations</li>\n<li>Users with limited or low vision</li>\n<li>Users with situational disabilities</li>\n<li>Users with temporary disabilities</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"what-is-the-real-roi-of-accessibility\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#what-is-the-real-roi-of-accessibility\" aria-label=\"what is the real roi of accessibility permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>What is the real ROI of accessibility</h2>\n<p>In new predictions we see that companies committing to accessibility will save a total of $ 10 billion to $ 16 billion in annual design spending across the U.S. and Canada. Accessibility isn’t a kryptonite for profits but it’s a money maker.</p>\n<p>By making your products accessible you add an additional multitude of people to your potential market. Secondly it optimizes your workflow by accounting for more issues beforehand. And the last but maybe the scariest part it will come back to bite you on the ass with the possibility of lawsuits and public exposure if you ignore accessibility.</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>“The cost of noncompliance is about three times higher than that of complying.”</p>\n</blockquote>\n<h2 id=\"what-can-you-do-to-make-your-business-more-compliant\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#what-can-you-do-to-make-your-business-more-compliant\" aria-label=\"what can you do to make your business more compliant permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>What can you do to make your business more compliant?</h2>\n<h3 id=\"1-start-by-making-your-teams-aware-of-what-theyre-missing\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#1-start-by-making-your-teams-aware-of-what-theyre-missing\" aria-label=\"1 start by making your teams aware of what theyre missing permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>1. Start by making your teams aware of what they’re missing</h3>\n<p>Having a training strategy in your business can drive your profit up to nearly 50%. When educating your team about accessibility, you’re not just giving them new skills to raise productivity, you’re optimizing their workflow for the long run and fostering a healthier team culture.</p>\n<h3 id=\"2-improve-testing-by-including-people-with-disabilities\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#2-improve-testing-by-including-people-with-disabilities\" aria-label=\"2 improve testing by including people with disabilities permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>2. Improve testing by including people with disabilities</h3>\n<p>It’s harder to fix the first row of bricks on a new house if you’re already building the second and third stories. Therefore, we need to rethink testing. Continuously trying out your product will tell you what needs tweaking as you advance. The problem is: people with disabilities are being excluded from the testing process. And even when they do appear in data sets, their data are often treated as anomalies because they don’t follow the patterns we’re used to seeing.</p>\n<p>This has a direct impact on your bottom line. Compliance issues cause a world of pain further on in your journey, when you’re paying hefty fines and rebuilding core elements of your product. These lawsuits are rising, last your over 2,500 were filed against website with bad accessibility.</p>\n<p>With accurate testing, your processes will become more efficient because you’re understanding where and when in your product lifecycle you need to insert tools and make changes to improve the accessibility.</p>\n<p><figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 780px; \"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 43.58974358974359%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Accessible websites can be useful to more populations than you might realize. Photo credit: deque.com\"\n        title=\"Accessible websites can be useful to more populations than you might realize. Photo credit: deque.com\"\n        src=\"/static/1f15a23cadbb37b7eb7d0cba61c6d814/be796/Picture-1.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/1f15a23cadbb37b7eb7d0cba61c6d814/4146e/Picture-1.jpg 195w,\n/static/1f15a23cadbb37b7eb7d0cba61c6d814/e52b6/Picture-1.jpg 390w,\n/static/1f15a23cadbb37b7eb7d0cba61c6d814/be796/Picture-1.jpg 780w,\n/static/1f15a23cadbb37b7eb7d0cba61c6d814/ad68d/Picture-1.jpg 1170w,\n/static/1f15a23cadbb37b7eb7d0cba61c6d814/62522/Picture-1.jpg 1560w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 780px) 100vw, 780px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\"><p>Accessible websites can be useful to more populations than you might realize. Photo credit: deque.com</p></figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<h3 id=\"3-evangelize-accessibility-within-your-team\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#3-evangelize-accessibility-within-your-team\" aria-label=\"3 evangelize accessibility within your team permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>3. Evangelize accessibility within your team</h3>\n<p>It’s everyone’s job to understand accessibility. However, there will always be people who are specifically focused on the job.</p>\n<p>Your long-term returns on assigning a few people to carry out the process accurately will always be higher than the initial expense. Those people will ensure each team is working optimally for all users.</p>\n<h2 id=\"what-do-we-at-ordina-do-to-ensure-accessibility\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#what-do-we-at-ordina-do-to-ensure-accessibility\" aria-label=\"what do we at ordina do to ensure accessibility permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>What do we at Ordina do to ensure accessibility?</h2>\n<h3 id=\"designing-with-the-user-in-mind\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#designing-with-the-user-in-mind\" aria-label=\"designing with the user in mind permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Designing with the user in mind</h3>\n<p>At Ordina, we strongly believe that accessibility is something which is part of our full design process and not just something to bolt on at the end in the form of colour &#x26; contrast.</p>\n<p>In our design discovery phase, we start by understanding the context and target audience for who we are designing. E.g., do think of your users who may not be able to access your website via either tool (mouse, keyboard, monitor…). Try to think of your users as broad as possible. Do this from the start of a project you’re working on, and you’ll be already a big step ahead!</p>\n<p>By having this crucial information, it’s important to define the right requirements for the right audience. Not only requirements that work for John Doe, but also requirements that make a product accessible to people with limited or low vision, cognitive limitations, situational disabilities, …</p>\n<p>Some of the techniques we use that help us to understand the context and target audience:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Contextual interviews</li>\n<li>Service safari’s</li>\n<li>Customer journey mapping</li>\n<li>Persona mapping</li>\n</ul>\n<p>While in the discovery phase we want to know more about the why &#x26; how, we tackle some more practical accessibility rules in our design delivery phase. Here we get to the level of creating accessible user interfaces by looking into colours, typography, sizing, etc. These kinds of practices are something that are baked into our design process by using a design system where accessibility plays a crucial role in the documentation and construction of the guidelines &#x26; components.</p>\n<p><figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 780px; \"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 56.41025641025641%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Buttons with good color contrast are easier to read. Photo credit: uxdesign.cc\"\n        title=\"Buttons with good color contrast are easier to read. Photo credit: uxdesign.cc\"\n        src=\"/static/45b323f238f35e9f236020b87bb877f9/be796/1_TD0is7b5AnqHtyhkVJ4Qsw.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/45b323f238f35e9f236020b87bb877f9/4146e/1_TD0is7b5AnqHtyhkVJ4Qsw.jpg 195w,\n/static/45b323f238f35e9f236020b87bb877f9/e52b6/1_TD0is7b5AnqHtyhkVJ4Qsw.jpg 390w,\n/static/45b323f238f35e9f236020b87bb877f9/be796/1_TD0is7b5AnqHtyhkVJ4Qsw.jpg 780w,\n/static/45b323f238f35e9f236020b87bb877f9/ad68d/1_TD0is7b5AnqHtyhkVJ4Qsw.jpg 1170w,\n/static/45b323f238f35e9f236020b87bb877f9/fcb1e/1_TD0is7b5AnqHtyhkVJ4Qsw.jpg 1452w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 780px) 100vw, 780px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\"><p>Buttons with good color contrast are easier to read. Photo credit: uxdesign.cc</p></figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<h3 id=\"developing-with-the-user-in-mind\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#developing-with-the-user-in-mind\" aria-label=\"developing with the user in mind permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Developing with the user in mind</h3>\n<p>From a developers standpoint, accessibility is knowing a bunch of ARIA tags, applying them on the right components. Choosing contrasting colours, and providing icons to indicate a state. And most importantly, putting an alt attribute on images.</p>\n<p>At least this is how almost every developers learns it from school but there is so much more we have to take into account when we talk about accessibility. You only need one dedicated lesson and from then on you never look back. At Ordina developers can take a two day course around accessibility.</p>\n<p>To fully test the accessibility of your website you need to invest in a screen reader, a braille display, unplug the hdmi and cut the cord of your mouse (or remove the batteries). Should your site be still usable at this point, pat yourself on the back, you are doing a great job. But for many projects, this isn’t the case.</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>“I, as a developer had the opportunity at Ordina to take a two-day course around accessibility.”</p>\n</blockquote>\n<h3 id=\"some-tips-on-how-you-can-learn-to-think-about-accessibility\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#some-tips-on-how-you-can-learn-to-think-about-accessibility\" aria-label=\"some tips on how you can learn to think about accessibility permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Some tips on how you can learn to think about accessibility</h3>\n<h4 id=\"drop-the-mouse-and-learn-from-your-keyboard\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#drop-the-mouse-and-learn-from-your-keyboard\" aria-label=\"drop the mouse and learn from your keyboard permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Drop the mouse and learn from your keyboard</h4>\n<p>While using assistive tools during your development would slow you down tremendously, even without learning braille, I would advise you to try using them one day to enjoy the experience. But for now, we need a quick way to test the basics of our application, preferably not too intrusive in our workflow. For that, dropping the mouse is not such a bad idea. By using your keyboard to navigate around a website, you get insight into how screen readers see it.</p>\n<p>Tab to navigate through interactive elements and Enter or Space to activate (click on) things. The arrows let you navigate through lists or manipulate interactive elements, like sliders or date pickers. Those are the basics. By using this keyboard method, you can discover if a site uses the right semantics in its html, that the developers used default components or if they spent a lot of time creating custom components that have all the usability features.</p>\n<h4 id=\"use-default-components\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#use-default-components\" aria-label=\"use default components permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Use default components</h4>\n<p>Sounds stupid enough right, use a button to click, an input to get data, … Until the moment you realise that you are happily putting click handlers on divs and spans and list items or custom components. We all did that and probably still do unknowingly on a Monday morning without a coffee.</p>\n<p>In this seat reservation tool, you can see the Monday blues. You have a list of dates where you can’t focus on, a beautiful floor plan with no focus on and a very usable form that only appears visible when you picked a date and a seat on the floor plan. Problem? Users with no mouse and only a keyboard can’t select a date or a seat so they can never reserve a seat.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 780px; \"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 56.41025641025641%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Picture 2\"\n        title=\"Picture 2\"\n        src=\"/static/581b7bc81fad64436613f95d2969de7d/be796/Picture-2.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/581b7bc81fad64436613f95d2969de7d/4146e/Picture-2.jpg 195w,\n/static/581b7bc81fad64436613f95d2969de7d/e52b6/Picture-2.jpg 390w,\n/static/581b7bc81fad64436613f95d2969de7d/be796/Picture-2.jpg 780w,\n/static/581b7bc81fad64436613f95d2969de7d/ad68d/Picture-2.jpg 1170w,\n/static/581b7bc81fad64436613f95d2969de7d/62522/Picture-2.jpg 1560w,\n/static/581b7bc81fad64436613f95d2969de7d/2c89e/Picture-2.jpg 1568w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 780px) 100vw, 780px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p>And what would have worked for everyone? A select to pick a date, a list of checkboxes to choose seats, and some dynamic inputs to enter names. Finally submit the whole thing with a button.</p>\n<p>There is a simple way to fix it: show the dates as a list of radio buttons, and the desks as a list of checkboxes. And so, you wrap the date components with a label tag, and add an invisible input for each, linked to the label using the for attribute. Then you wrap it together with a reactive form, so you can remove some click handlers afterwards. In terms of styling this sums it up: input:focus + label.</p>\n<h4 id=\"testing-is-key\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#testing-is-key\" aria-label=\"testing is key permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Testing is key</h4>\n<p>It improves both the clean code and reusability, surplus it might improve testability, because Selenium is a screen reader in disguise. Think about what your code is going to accomplish, and make sure that flow works in all circumstances. Pick a date, choose a chair, enter your name, and save. It can be a simple form, usable, accessible, and boring. All the bells and whistles you add, should not make it harder to get its job done.</p>\n<p>You must adapt your workflow. When you develop a feature throw together some inputs, selects and buttons. Make the features work with a keyboard and only then start making it look attractive.</p>\n<h3 id=\"some-tips-on-how-you-can-learn-to-think-about-accessibility-1\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#some-tips-on-how-you-can-learn-to-think-about-accessibility-1\" aria-label=\"some tips on how you can learn to think about accessibility 1 permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Some tips on how you can learn to think about accessibility</h3>\n<p>As a designer or developer, you find many challenges in your work. We have our favourites, so why not add accessibility? The only advice you need to hear is: Go around, use your keyboard on random websites or try to fill in forms on your smartphone with a scaled screen and find yourself annoyed. Then do it better on your next project.</p>","headings":[{"depth":2,"value":"Introduction","id":"introduction"},{"depth":2,"value":"Digital accessibility","id":"digital-accessibility"},{"depth":2,"value":"What is the real ROI of accessibility","id":"what-is-the-real-roi-of-accessibility"},{"depth":2,"value":"What can you do to make your business more compliant?","id":"what-can-you-do-to-make-your-business-more-compliant"},{"depth":3,"value":"1. Start by making your teams aware of what they’re missing","id":"1-start-by-making-your-teams-aware-of-what-theyre-missing"},{"depth":3,"value":"2. Improve testing by including people with disabilities","id":"2-improve-testing-by-including-people-with-disabilities"},{"depth":3,"value":"3. Evangelize accessibility within your team","id":"3-evangelize-accessibility-within-your-team"},{"depth":2,"value":"What do we at Ordina do to ensure accessibility?","id":"what-do-we-at-ordina-do-to-ensure-accessibility"},{"depth":3,"value":"Designing with the user in mind","id":"designing-with-the-user-in-mind"},{"depth":3,"value":"Developing with the user in mind","id":"developing-with-the-user-in-mind"},{"depth":3,"value":"Some tips on how you can learn to think about accessibility","id":"some-tips-on-how-you-can-learn-to-think-about-accessibility"},{"depth":4,"value":"Drop the mouse and learn from your keyboard","id":"drop-the-mouse-and-learn-from-your-keyboard"},{"depth":4,"value":"Use default components","id":"use-default-components"},{"depth":4,"value":"Testing is key","id":"testing-is-key"},{"depth":3,"value":"Some tips on how you can learn to think about accessibility","id":"some-tips-on-how-you-can-learn-to-think-about-accessibility-1"}],"frontmatter":{"title":"How good accessibility improves user experiences & business profit","category":"Accessibility","tags":["Accessibility"],"image":{"childImageSharp":{"gatsbyImageData":{"layout":"fullWidth","backgroundColor":"#484858","images":{"fallback":{"src":"/static/b6f4e68d2043a4226b8e448a5df7f044/e